6.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 任, based on its Mandarin pronunciation, see   Ren   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 全, based on its pronunciation in Shanghai dialect, see   Quan   2.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 曾, see   Zeng  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ren","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Yong, Hong, Hui, Chuan, Gang, Guang, Jian, Liang, Lihua, Ning, Qing, Chang, Min, Shen, Yiming.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 任, a term for women's rank of peerage in ancient Chinese: (i) it is said that the surname can be traced back to one of the 25 sons of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (ii) from Ren (任), the name of an ancient state (located in Renxian in Hebei province) granted to Yu Yang, said to be a son or grandson of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the state as their surname. (iii) from Ren (任), the name of a state (located in Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","English: variant of   Renn   2."]}]},{"name":"Santerre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ovila, Pierre.","French: habitational name from a region in Picardy, located to the southeast of the Somme river, named with Latin <i>sana terra</i> ‘healthy, wholesome land’, and perhaps also from Le Santerre, the name of several places in the northern part of France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"François","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval name meaning ‘French’.  See  <b>Francis</b>   . Its popularity in France has been greatly influenced by Italian <i>Francesco</i> and the fame of St Francis of Assisi."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When François de Rosière